    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense from a carbon reduction standpoint. But looking at the social side, isn't there a real danger that this just ends up being a penalty on people who don't have the luxury of living near a subway line or who have to drive for work? How would you address the argument that these policies are basically just a tax on the working class while the wealthy can just pay the fee and keep driving?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that congestion pricing is a tax on the working class is a persistent, politically charged objection that fundamentally relies on the premise that the current system is fair. To address this, successful models must implement robust exemptions and significant reinvestment into transit equity. When revenue is explicitly earmarked to improve bus routes, increase service frequency in underserved neighborhoods, and offer low-income transit passes, the policy shifts from being a punitive tax to a necessary investment in public infrastructure that benefits everyone.",
